While Ri repeated the famous North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to the “progressive” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for every step, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had been through it in the past.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12 when Kim undertook to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees of security to North Korea.
North Korea is pursuing a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first surrender its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the calls to release severe international sanctions against North Korea.
“The US insists on “denuclearization first” and increases the pressure on sanctions to force its targets and even object to the “declaration of the end of the war”, said Ri.
