Harvard students are taking a course to teach them enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University forced all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of macho studies all night long, when students do not sleep and encourage caffeine.
The academics found that students at the world’s most famous university are often clueless when it comes to the basics of self - care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Hospital and the female hospital, who he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to begin the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, which was first presented this year, explains to students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's medical services, said that the university decided to set up a course after finding that the students had been seriously ill during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part there is a picture of student dormitories, where students click on cups with coffee, curtains, sneakers and books on the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleeping habits.
In another part, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that students’ behavior will not change immediately.
However, we believe that they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the effects of smoking cigarettes on health," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, he added that modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Enough sleep of good quality should be a “secret weapon” of a student to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain into a hunger mode, so that one is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical biology in California, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes attended last year during her first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to press the course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study programme before entering a competitive institution.
The professor recommended that students consider setting the alarm for the time when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that may upset your circadian rhythm, leading to difficulty falling asleep.
