The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to the overall decline in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, stains of blooming water are now reported from the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this indicates a declining concentration.
The blooming water of the red tide extends about 130 miles of coastline from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
The stains were observed about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but last week it was already relatively fewer places.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
In Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations were observed, the lowest to high concentrations in Manatee County, the lowest to high concentrations in the coast or in the high seas of Sarasota County, the lowest to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, the lowest to high concentrations in the coast or in the high seas of Lee County and the low concentrations in Collier County were observed.
Respiratory irritations continue to occur in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
